Along with all the other platform information that Confluence collects for a support bundle, we should collect the output from lsb_release -a, which will tell us which distribution and version the server is as well. Right now, we only get the linux kernel package version, which doesn't tell us much about what sort of localization support they have, what permission environment they're likely to have (do they have to use sudo for all admin tasks, or do they login as root?), or what sort of installation process they're being subjected to. With the distribution info from lsb_release, we could better focus our efforts in getting improved installers, and better replicate the environment of our users on support cases.

When using custom HTML for footer under "Administration->Look and Feel->Custom HTML-> At End of the BODY", which adds a large block of code, the rest of the body is pushed upwards and out of the screen.
Making the #footer relative in {{default-style.css}} helps in resolving the problem:
{noformat}
#footer {
bottom:0;
position:relative;
width:100%;
}
{noformat}

h5. Description
When round-tripping between Rich Text Editor and Wiki Markup in a page that contains macros which has body as headings, the formatting of bullets inside the macro breaks. Please check the next section for more information

h5. Steps to Reproduce
# Copy the wiki markup below and paste to a Wiki Markup editor, then switch between Rich Text Editor and Wiki Markup.
{noformat}
h1. {panel}
* bullet 1
* bullet 2
{panel}
{noformat}
[^bug_1.jpg]
# This is how it suppose to look like in Preview:
[^bug_2.jpg]
# Switch to Rich Text Editor and back to Wiki Markup mode, this is how it will look:
[^bug_3.jpg]
# Switch to Rich Text Editor and back to Wiki Markup mode again, a backslash is added to the bullet:
[^bug_4.jpg]
# This is how it suppose to look like in Preview mode:
[^bug_5.jpg]

\\
h5. Findings
This bug also affects the following macros:
- \{panel}
- \{section}
- \{column}
- \{note}
- \{info}
- \{tip}
- \{warning}

h5. Workaround
Just write the macro in a newline, example below:
{noformat}
h1.
{panel}
* bullet 1
* bullet 2
{panel}
{noformat}

