Confluence is still using the legacy license API (deprecated 2 years ago).  The new license API supports embedding and extracting arbitrary keys out of the license.  This functionality would be really useful for Studio with Balsamiq and Gliffy licenses.  We currently have deals with Balsamiq and Gliffy that allow us to bundle them with Studio, however, the licenses are maintained separately, which is a pain to maintain.  What we would like to do is add the Balsamiq/Gliffy license as custom properties to the Confluence license in the Studio license, that way there is only one license to maintain.  The Balsamiq developers have indicated they would be happy to support this, and we're assuming Gliffy would be ok too.  We can do this now, except because Confluence is using the legacy license API, there's no way for the Balsamiq plugin to read these custom properties from the license.

Reported by Chris:

{quote}
Confluence has a bug (which I originally thought was in the UWC) in the way it parses wiki markup. Originally discovered while trying to import a mediawiki instance into confluence I have found that the wiki markup parser fails to render images under a given circumstance.

This link points to my comments on the UWC forum about it
http://forums.atlassian.com/message.jspa?messageID=257346941#257346941

Essentially the problem is if you follow some wikimarkup with a non whitespace character the markup is escaped and the code not rendered.

so
{noformat}!image.jpg|align=right!Bla Bla Bla{noformat}

fails to render and the markup is changed to

{noformat}\!image.jpg\|align=right\!Bla Bla Bla{noformat}

Thus inline images fail, Other markup may fail due to this but I haven't tested it.
{quote}

